    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "**Describe the bug**\r\nUsing a `ctypedef` to give a different name to a fused type does not lead to different specialisations when used in a function argument list.\r\n\r\n**To Reproduce**\r\nCode to reproduce the behaviour:\r\n```cython\r\nctypedef fused xx:\r\n    int\r\n    double\r\n    \r\nctypedef xx yy\r\n\r\ncdef ffunc(xx a, yy b):\r\n    return xx is yy, xx is int, yy is int\r\n\r\nprint(ffunc(1, 1))\r\nprint(ffunc(1.0, 2.0))\r\nprint(ffunc(1, 2.0))\r\nprint(ffunc(1.0, 2))\r\n```\r\nprints\r\n```\r\n(True, True, True)\r\n(True, False, False)\r\n(True, False, False)\r\n(True, False, False)\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Expected behavior**\r\nIt should behave like\r\n```cython\r\nctypedef fused xx:\r\n    int\r\n    double\r\n\r\nctypedef fused yy:\r\n    int\r\n    double\r\n\r\ncdef ffunc(xx a, yy b):\r\n    return xx is yy, xx is int, yy is int\r\n\r\nprint(ffunc(1, 1))\r\nprint(ffunc(1.0, 2.0))\r\nprint(ffunc(1, 2.0))\r\nprint(ffunc(1.0, 2))\r\n```\r\nwhich prints\r\n```\r\n(True, True, True)\r\n(True, False, False)\r\n(False, True, False)\r\n(False, False, True)\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Environment (please complete the following information):**\r\n - OS: Linux\r\n - Python version: 3.8.10\r\n - Cython version: 3.0.0a8 (also tested with 0.25.x and later)\r\n",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "The problem is here:\r\nhttps://github.com/cython/cython/blob/c9a428789ff5fe919d21fbc238a4c8504161ad24/Cython/Compiler/PyrexTypes.py#L403\r\n\r\nFor fused types, we declare the type entry with the base type instead of the typedef type, which means that the function then doesn't know any more that the arguments were really declared with different type names, because the arguments really have the exact same type.\r\n\r\nRemoving the special case leads to parser errors (likely failures to parse types), so there are probably other hurdles down that road.",
